    <a href="/reading/cogsci/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to cognitive science</a>

    <h1>Language and Communication</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Lovelace textbook &middot; CC BY-SA 4.0 &middot; <a href="https://computationalcognitivescience.github.io/lovelace/home">computationalcognitivescience.github.io/lovelace/home</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Language is a <strong>noisy channel</strong> between minds. The speaker encodes a meaning, the channel (speech, text) introduces noise, and the listener decodes. <strong>Surprisal</strong> measures how unexpected a word is: high-surprisal words slow reading. <strong>Pragmatic inference</strong> goes beyond literal meaning: listeners reason about what the speaker <em>chose</em> to say and what they could have said instead.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Shannon's communication model -->
    <h3>The communication channel</h3>
    <p>Shannon's model: a sender encodes a message, transmits it through a noisy channel, and a receiver decodes it. The fundamental theorem of information theory says that reliable communication is possible at any rate below the channel capacity. Language production and comprehension fit this framework: the speaker compresses meaning into words, the listener decompresses.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Shannon's communication model -->
